Let $y(x)$ be continuous solution of initial value problem $\frac{dy}{dx}+2y=f(x),y(0)=0$. Where $f(x) = \left\{ \begin{array}{rcl}
1 & \mbox{for}
& 0 \leq x\leq 1 \\ 0 & \mbox{for} & x>1 
\end{array}\right.$ Then FInd $y(\frac{3}{2})$ Answer is $\frac{sinh(1)}{e^2}$ I have tried the following: It is a linear differential equation $\therefore $Multiplying each term by $e^{\int 2dx}=e^{2x}$ $\therefore \frac{d}{dx}\left(y.e^{2x}\right)=e^{2x}f(x)$ $\therefore y(e^{2x})=\int e^{2x}.f(x) dx$ $\therefore y=e^{-2x}\int e^{2x}.f(x).dx$

$X=\mathbb{N}_0$ and  $Y= \left\lbrace \frac{1}{n} ~|~ n\in \mathbb{N}  \right\rbrace \cup \left\lbrace 0\right\rbrace $ are subspaces of euclidean space $\mathbb{R}$. See if function $f: X \to Y $ $  f(n) =
